            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-terminology-and-notation.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory III › Terminology and notation"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii" title="Hodge Theory III">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Terminology and notation</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1884</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.1</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> be a continuous map between topological spaces.
    We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>proper</fr:em> if it is proper in the sense of Bourbaki (i.e. universally closed) and furthermore separated (i.e. the diagonal of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\times _Y X]]></fr:tex> is closed).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1885</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.2</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Following Gabriel and Zisman, we say <fr:em>simplicial</fr:em> where we would have previously said semi-simplicial.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1886</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.3</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> a Noetherian subring of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\otimes \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is a field.
    The useful cases are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1887</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.4</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>mixed Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-structure</fr:em> consists of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_A]]></fr:tex> of finite type, a finite increasing filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> on the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\otimes \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}=H_A\otimes \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, and a finite decreasing filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>-vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}=H_A\otimes _A\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
    We demand that the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H_{A\otimes \mathbb {Q}}),\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(F))]]></fr:tex> be Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\otimes \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures.
    For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> (resp. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>), we recover <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.1.xml" taxon="Definition" number="2.3.1" /> (resp. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.8.xml" number="2.3.8" />);
    the results of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.xml" number="2.3" /> carry over as they are.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1888</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.5</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {E}]]></fr:tex> be a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}\times \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.
    We say that a mixed Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is of <fr:em>degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {E}]]></fr:tex></fr:em> if the Hodge numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{pq}]]></fr:tex> are zero for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)\not \in \mathscr {E}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1889</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.6</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>From now on, we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _X^\bullet (\log  D)]]></fr:tex> what we previously denoted by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _X^\bullet \langle  D\rangle ]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2.xml" number="3.1.2" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1890</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-0.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-0.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>III.0.7</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Unless explicitly stated otherwise, <fr:em>scheme</fr:em> means "scheme of finite type over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>", and a <fr:em>sheaf</fr:em> on a scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a sheaf on the underlying topological space of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\mathrm {an}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
